@Rylowery11 Not true, plenty of corporate and institutional interest already

Yes a tokenized state instead of tokenizing via the retirement function would be more clean

Disagree about needing two way bridge for offsetting

@SevNightingale That is one alternative

If there was a safe way to bridge assets I would be more inclined to this view

Any other similar network technology that has not consolidated over time?

@timrann Agree - it is a tough but super important challenge

As you point out, even after appropriately designing such systems, bringing in proper representation is another tough problem

There might never be "perfect" governance, but hopefully we are moving in the right direction

@finrenton @danielrion 100% agree, believe @ReFiDAOist is one of the most positive forces helping shape ReFi for the planet

That's such a good point, engagement should play a much larger role in determining governance power

Any good examples of engagement based voting? Curious how to measure it best

@jessewldn @RvrsToken Shareholders in an LLC can only indirectly push for extraction through board selection/articles etc.

With plain token voting, tokenholders will directly influence policies in favor of extraction

Though DAOs have more flexibility to customize token voting design than LLCs

@nic__carter @thetrocro Using on-chain carbon such as @ToucanProtocol $NCT or $BCT you could easily program a contract that will offset all of your BTC footprint automatically with full fungibility

Eg @ReturnProtocol are doing this for Ethereum blockspace use

DMs open if you want to explore this

@alhudecki @tmoindustries Love where you are going with this

In a way I think ReFi should go beyond just offsetting emissions but create abundant positive externalities

Eg Toucan using 50% of its redemption fee to offset, this is probably many times larger than our footprint üòé
